# Failure Case Analysis

Common ways models get things wrong on our benchmark.

## 1. Wrong Target

The model picks up sentiment about the wrong company or entity.

| Input | Expected | Model Said | What Went Wrong |
|-------|----------|------------|-----------------|
| "Tesla stock dropped 5% after strong Ford earnings report" | Negative | Positive | Focused on Ford's "strong earnings" instead of Tesla's drop |
| "Despite Apple's record quarter, suppliers face margin pressure" | Negative | Positive | Picked up on "record quarter" and ignored the supplier issue |

Models tend to latch onto the strongest positive/negative words without checking *who* the question is actually about.

## 2. Doesn't Understand Finance

The model misses things that a finance person would catch.
| Input | Expected | Model Said | What Went Wrong |
|-------|----------|------------|-----------------|
| "The company announced a reverse stock split" | Negative | Neutral | Didn't know reverse splits are usually a bad sign |
| "Short interest in XYZ rose to 25%" | Negative | Neutral | Didn't recognize high short interest as bearish |

General-purpose models just don't always know what specific financial terms or events mean for investors.

## 3. Right Info, Wrong Answer

The model finds the relevant facts but still gets the conclusion wrong.

| Input | Expected | Model Said | What Went Wrong |
|-------|----------|------------|-----------------|
| "Revenue grew 3% vs expected 8% growth" | Negative | Positive | Saw "grew" and said positive, missed the expectation gap |
| "EPS beat estimates by $0.02 but guidance was lowered" | Negative | Positive | Focused on the small beat, ignored the guidance cut |

This happens when there are competing signals — the model picks the surface-level one instead of the one that actually matters more.

## 4. Defaulting to Neutral

The model plays it safe and says "neutral" when it should commit to positive or negative.

| Input | Expected | Model Said | What Went Wrong |
|-------|----------|------------|-----------------|
| "The Fed held rates steady amid mixed economic signals" | Positive | Neutral | Markets saw the hold as dovish, but the model hedged |
| "Management expressed cautious optimism about Q4" | Positive | Neutral | The word "cautious" scared it into neutral |

When the input has any kind of hedging language, models tend to default to neutral instead of making a call.

## Takeaways

- Models need to be told exactly *which* entity to evaluate sentiment for
- Financial domain knowledge matters a lot — general models miss things
- Beating expectations vs missing expectations is a hard concept for models
- Models are too cautious and overuse the neutral label
